reason.tex:
%text Before thinking about integrating factors and other stuff - why not take 10 seconds to \underline\text{observe the equation}?
In particular, given an equation of the form \[ P(x)\frac{dy}{dx} + Q(x) y = R(x) \] \underline\text{ask yourself whether \[Q(x) = \frac{d}{dx} P(x) \]}
Because if it is - as in this case - then % \begin{align} P(x)\frac{dy}{dx} + Q(x) y &= R(x) \\ \implies \underbrace{\frac{d}{dx}\lbrace P(x)\cdot y \rbrace }_{P(x)\frac{dy}{dx} + Q(x) y} &= R(x) \end{align}

\begin{align}
\frac{d}{dx}\lbrace (x^2-1)\cdot y \rbrace &= \frac{1}{x^2-1} \\
\implies (x^2-1)\cdot y &= \int\frac{dx}{x^2-1} \\
&= \underbrace{\frac{1}{2}\log\left\vert \frac{x-1}{x+1}\right\vert}_{\int\frac{dx}{x^2-a^2} = \frac{1}{2a}\log\left\vert \frac{x-a}{x+a}\right\vert + C } + C \\
\therefore y &= \frac{1}{x^2-1}\cdot\left[ \frac{1}{2}\log\left\vert \frac{x-1}{x+1}\right\vert + C\right]
\end{align}
